ce you finish testing, you can probably roll your cars out broadly.=C2=A0</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another way to test them is to just send out=
 a bunch of cars to drive themselves everywhere, without asking for permiss=
ion,=C2=A0and see what happens. If they all do great, then you announce =E2=
=80=9Chey we have perfect self-driving cars, they=E2=80=99ve been driving e=
verywhere for months now with no crashes, aren=E2=80=99t we great?=E2=80=9D=
 And then regulators come to you and say =E2=80=9Cwait, you can=E2=80=99t s=
ell these self-driving cars, we need to study and test them for a few more =
years,=E2=80=9D and you go to the press and say =E2=80=9Cthese regulators a=
re holding up progress, people will die while they refuse to approve our sa=
fe self-driving cars,=E2=80=9D and you will not be wrong, and the press and=
 the public will be on your side and you will steamroll the regulators.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, if you send out those cars =
to drive themselves everywhere and they all crash and kill a bunch of peopl=
e, that will be bad! You will be in bad trouble.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s=
 better to ask forgiveness than to ask permission,=E2=80=9D you will say, b=
ut this is not quite right; maybe it is better to=C2=A0<em>announce success=
=C2=A0</em>and then smugly add =E2=80=9Csorry we didn=E2=80=99t tell you fi=
rst,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0but it is strictly worse to fail catastrophically=C2=A0a=
nd apologize. If you are going to fail it is better to ask permission, beca=
use forgiveness will not be forthcoming. If you are going to succeed, sure,=
 it is better to ask forgiveness. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s nothing to forgi=
ve, you=E2=80=99re perfect, you little scamp,=E2=80=9D everyone will reply.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are doing some bold novel thing, yo=
